using the quicksort algorithm, we can sort an unsorted array of integers in place, by first choosing a pivot element from the array, and then partitioning the array into two sub-arrays such that all elements less than or equal to the pivot are in the left sub-array and all elements greater than the pivot are in the right sub-array. Then, we recursively sort the left and right sub-arrays until the array is sorted.

Here is an implementation of the quicksort algorithm in C#:

```
public static void QuickSort(int[] array, int left, int right)
{
    if (left < right)
    {
        int pivotIndex = Partition(array, left, right);
        QuickSort(array, left, pivotIndex - 1);
        QuickSort(array, pivotIndex + 1, right);
    }
}

// Finds the index of the pivot element in the given array and returns it.
private static int Partition(int[] array, int left, int right)
{
    int pivotIndex = left;
    while (left <= right)
    {
        while (left < right && array[right] < array[left])
            right--;
        while (left < right && array[left] > array[right])
            left++;

        if (left < right)
            exchange(array, left, right);

        if (left == right - 1)
            break;
        else if (array[left] < array[right])
            left++;
        else
            right--;
    }

    if (left < right)
        exchange(array, left, right);

    return pivotIndex;
}

// Swaps the elements at the given indices.
private static void exchange(int[] array, int left, int right)
{
    int tmp = array[left];
    array[left] = array[right];
    array[right] = tmp;
}
```

